1. ICC is used in reproducibility studies. Calculate ICC of zcor using the original definition. The original definition is defined similar to Pearsons correlation but uses a shared mean: \[ \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n((y_{i1} - \bar{y}_{\cdot \cdot})(y_{i2}-\bar{y}_{\cdot \cdot})/var(y_{ij}),\] where \(y_{\cdot \cdot} = \frac{1}{2n} \sum_{i=1}^n \sum_{j=1}^2 y_{ij}\) and \(var(y_{ij})=\sum_{i=1}^n \sum_{j=1}^2 (y_{ij} - \bar{y}_{\cdot \cdot})^2/(2n)\). Here, \(j=1\) corresponds to SB.3.3.mm and \(j=2\) corresponds to MB.4. In order to do this, if a subject is missing zcor for SB.3.3.mm or MB.4, remove that subject from the calculation

library(tidyr)
# reshape data into wide format
mbdata_sel_wide = mbdata_sel %>% 
  select(id, Acquisition, zcor) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = Acquisition, values_from = zcor) 
# remove subject with missing 'zcor' for SB.3.3.mm or MB.4
mbdata_sel_wide_complete = mbdata_sel_wide[complete.cases(mbdata_sel_wide),]
zcor.SB = unlist(mbdata_sel_wide_complete[,'SB.3.3.mm'])
zcor.MB = unlist(mbdata_sel_wide_complete[,'MB.4'])

# calculate the shared mean \bar{y}
y_bar = mean(c(zcor.SB, zcor.MB))
# calculate var(y_{ij})
var_yij = mean(c((zcor.SB - y_bar)^2, (zcor.MB - y_bar)^2))
# calculate icc
icc = (mean((zcor.SB - y_bar) * (zcor.MB - y_bar)))/ (var_yij)
print(icc)
## [1] -0.1218052

3. Calculate the mixed model formulation of ICC. This more modern approach allows the use of participants that may be missing a first or second scan. Then based on the guidelines for reproducibility below, how is the reproducibility of brain activity between the two acquisitions?

Less than 0.40poor.

Between 0.40 and 0.59fair.

Between 0.60 and 0.74good.

Between 0.75 and 1.00excellent.

# extract tau^2 and sigma^2
tau2 <- VarCorr(model0)$id[1]
sigma2 <- summary(model0)$sigma^2

# compute icc
icc <- tau2 / (tau2 + sigma2)
print(icc)
## [1] 0

The mixed model formulation of ICC is 0, indicating poor reproducibility of brain activity between the two acquisitions.

5. Write the model for problem 4. R markdown can use latex (pronounced lay-tek) notation to create Greek letters. If you are compiling your homework in html, you may be able to compile this without installing additional software. If you encounter issues, you can try typing tinytex::install_tinytex() in the R Console. There are examples above in problem 1. Here is another example: \[y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \epsilon_i\] \[\epsilon_i \overset{iid}{\sim} N(0,\sigma^2).\] Make sure to use two indices when appropriate, e.g., \(y_{ij}\). Use \(\tau^2\) for the random intercept variance. (Note: use a single dollar sign for in-line equations, and two dollars signs for an equation on a new line, see this R markdown file.) Define all notation.

\[ y_{ij} = \mu + \theta_i + \beta \times \text{Acquisition}_{ij} + \epsilon_{ij} \]

We assume:

\[ \theta_i \stackrel{iid}{\sim} N(0, \tau^2)\\ \epsilon_{ij} \stackrel{iid}{\sim} N(0, \sigma^2) \\ \theta_i \perp \!\!\! \perp \epsilon_{ij} \]

  • \(y_{ij}\): the \(j^{th}\) measure of zcor for \(i^{th}\) subject;
  • \(\mu\): population intercept;
  • \(\theta_i\): difference of \(i^{th}\) subjects intercept from \(\mu\);
  • \(\text{Acquisition}_{ij}\): = 1 if MB.4 was used to acquire the \(j^{th}\) measure for \(i^{th}\) subject, = 0 if SB.3.3.mm was used;
  • \(\beta\): fixed effect of Acquisition on zcor;
  • \(\epsilon_{ij}\): measurement error of the \(j^{th}\) measure of zcor for \(i^{th}\) subject;
  • \(\tau^2\): between-group variability in the intercepts;
  • \(\sigma^2\): within-group variability in the residuals;

9. Read the section Diagnostics in Bates et al, Fitting Linear Mixed-Effects Models Using lme4, Journal of Statistical Software, 2015. Perform model diagnostics by creating the three plots described there (fitted versus residual, scale-location, and quantile-quantile plots). Note you will need the library lattice to use qqmath(). Are there any potential issues?

plot(model1.8, type = c("p", "smooth"),
     xlab = "Fitted", ylab = "Residual")

The fitted versus residual plot is used to check the linearity assumption and homoscedasticity. The blue line is not flat, which indicates a violation of the linearity assumption. The residuals are more spread out for large fitted values, indicating a violation of homoscedasticity.

plot(model1.8, sqrt(abs(resid(.))) ~ fitted(.), type = c("p", "smooth"),
     xlab = "Fitted", ylab = "Square Root of Residual")

The scale-location plot is used to check the homoscedasticity. The blue line is not flat, which indicates a violation of homoscedasticity.

library(lattice)
qqmath(model1.8, id = 0.05)

The quantile-quantile plot is used to assess the normality assumption. While there are some departures in the tails, the normality assumption is not a major concern in this case.

10. In multiple regression, we examined the influence of single data points by examining how the model changed when that data point was removed. In mixed models, we can examine the influence of removing one subject. We will do this using a package called influence.ME. Plot the Cooks distances that are calculated by refitting the model after removing one subject. This can be done adapting the following code chunk: plot(influence(mymixedmodel,group='id'),which='cook'). Are there any large issues?

library(influence.ME)
## 
## Attaching package: 'influence.ME'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     influence
plot(influence(model1.8, group = "id"), which="cook", sort=TRUE,
xlab="Cook's Distance",
ylab="ID")

The Cook distances are scaled differently than in multiple regression. In Nieuwenhuis et al, the authors use a cutoff of 4/(number of subjects). No subjects have Cooks distance exceed the threshold 4/32 = 0.125.

11. Now test the hypothesis that acquisition has a significant effect on the z-transformed correlations when controlling for gender and scanner type. Summarize your findings using complete sentences, stating the result, test statistic, degrees of freedom, and p-value.

model1.8_ml <- lmer(zcor~Acquisition+gender+scanner+(1|id), data = mbdata,REML=FALSE)
model1.8_reduced_ml <- lmer(zcor~gender+scanner+(1|id), data = mbdata,REML=FALSE)
anova(model1.8_reduced_ml, model1.8_ml)
## Data: mbdata
## Models:
## model1.8_reduced_ml: zcor ~ gender + scanner + (1 | id)
## model1.8_ml: zcor ~ Acquisition + gender + scanner + (1 | id)
##                     npar     AIC     BIC logLik deviance  Chisq Df Pr(>Chisq)
## model1.8_reduced_ml    5 135.300 153.420 -62.65  125.300                     
## model1.8_ml           13 -48.161  -1.049  37.08  -74.161 199.46  8  < 2.2e-16
##                        
## model1.8_reduced_ml    
## model1.8_ml         ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The likelihood ratio test yields a chi-squared statistic of 199.46 with 8 degrees of freedom. The corresponding p-value is less than \(2.2 \times 10^{-16}\), which is below the significance level of 0.05. We reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the acquisition has a significant effect on the z-transformed correlations when controlling for gender and scanner type.

# create an empty plot

# add predicted subject-specific estimates
ids = as.numeric(unique(pdata$subject))

  x = range(pdata$s_test_time[pdata$subject==i])
  beta = as.numeric(coef(model2.6)$subject[i, c('(Intercept)', 's_test_time')])

8. Conduct a likelihood ratio test for the model with versus without random slope. Which model is preferred?

model2.6_ml = lmer(motor_UPDRS~s_age+sex+Jitter_Percent+Shimmer+NHR+PPE+s_test_time+(s_test_time|subject),
                   data=pdata, REML=FALSE)
model2.8 = lmer(motor_UPDRS~s_age+sex+Jitter_Percent+Shimmer+NHR+PPE+s_test_time+(1|subject),
                data=pdata,REML=FALSE)
anova(model2.8, model2.6_ml)
## Data: pdata
## Models:
## model2.8: motor_UPDRS ~ s_age + sex + Jitter_Percent + Shimmer + NHR + PPE + s_test_time + (1 | subject)
## model2.6_ml: motor_UPDRS ~ s_age + sex + Jitter_Percent + Shimmer + NHR + PPE + s_test_time + (s_test_time | subject)
##             npar   AIC   BIC logLik deviance  Chisq Df Pr(>Chisq)    
## model2.8      10 26523 26590 -13252    26503                         
## model2.6_ml   12 20225 20305 -10100    20201 6302.5  2  < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The likelihood ratio test yields a chi-squared statistic of 6302.5 with 2 degrees of freedom. The corresponding p-value is less than \(2.2 \times 10^{-16}\), which is below the significance level of 0.05. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis that the variance of the random slope is equal to zero and conclude that the random slope model is preferred.

9. Recall that the p-values for likelihood ratio tests of random effects tend to be too large, and similarly, the AIC can select overly simple models, which is a consequence of the null hypothesis being on the boundary of the parameter space (i.e., variance = 0). We will calculate a simulation-based p-value for the restricted likelihood ratio test (i.e., from REML). Unfortunately, the simulation approach assumes the random effects are uncorrelated. Refit the model with the random slope and intercept uncorrelated using REML. Then use the function exactRLRT() to test the null hypothesis that the variance of the random slope is equal to zero. Which model is preferred? The code below is from the help manual for exactRLRT().

library(RLRsim)
data(sleepstudy, package = "lme4")
mA <- lme4::lmer(Reaction ~ I(Days-4.5) + (1|Subject) + (0 + I(Days-4.5)|Subject),
data = sleepstudy)
m0 <- update(mA, . ~ . - (0 + I(Days-4.5)|Subject))
m.slope <- update(mA, . ~ . - (1|Subject))
#test for subject specific slopes:
exactRLRT(m.slope, mA, m0)
## 
##  simulated finite sample distribution of RLRT.
##  
##  (p-value based on 10000 simulated values)
## 
## data:  
## RLRT = 32.916, p-value < 2.2e-16
mA <- lme4::lmer(motor_UPDRS~s_age+sex+Jitter_Percent+Shimmer+NHR+PPE+s_test_time+(1|subject)+(0+s_test_time|subject),
data = pdata)
m0 <- update(mA, . ~ . - (0+s_test_time|subject))
m.slope <- update(mA, . ~ . - (1|subject))
#test for subject specific slopes:
exactRLRT(m.slope, mA, m0)
## 
##  simulated finite sample distribution of RLRT.
##  
##  (p-value based on 10000 simulated values)
## 
## data:  
## RLRT = 6302.6, p-value < 2.2e-16

The p-value of the restricted likelihood ratio test is \(<\) 2.2e-16, which is below the significance level of 0.05. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis that the variance of the random slope is equal to zero and conclude that the random slope model is preferred.
